content.description: The crux is down low moving over the first bolt. Please note that clipping the first bolt can be a little scary if you're not confident at the grade. The next 3 bolts the climbing stays nice and consistent and this is the only reason I'd say it deserves the 10a rating.
content.location: Furthest right climb on the wall. This route is just barely to the right of barrier reef. Pay attention to the bolts as you go up. White Whale uses the glue in bolts and Barrier Reef uses the mechanical. Yes these routes are that close together...

content.description: Look for a small roof and right-facing corner. Climb through this on the right. The climbing through the roof is juggy and straight forward.
content.protection: This route is fully bolted (7 bolts), but is easily led entirely on gear (small cams to #0.5 Camalot, plus a #2 Camalot should suffice). Two bolts with chains on top, or walk off.
content.location: There is a large, obvious, and easy crack (also fully bolted) at about 1/3 of the way on the cliff from right to left. Immediately to the left of this is the Unknown 5.7+; this route is immediately left of the 5.7+.

content.description: Farthest left route on the Outback Wall.  Good climbing at 5.6 grade and then once you get to about  the 3 bolt. Slab up to the chains with very easy climbing.  Lots of rope drag
content.location: Far left side of the Outback Wall.

content.description: This crack is located directly below a small pine tree toward the left end of the outcrop.  It is immediately right of a corner which leads to a gently sloped ramp adjacent to a right facing dihedral.  The crack starts slightly left leaning and about mid-way the crack is slightly right leaning.  The face climbing to the side of the crack is easy.  There is still some moss--I cleaned it as I went the first time.  At the top sling the tree for protection and continue up the ramp to bolts and chains--this part needs more parties and some easy cleaning.  This is a nice moderate climb for someone new to placing gear who wants some practice.  The route name is meant to be a word play on terms an organic chemist will appreciate and find fun.
content.protection: Gear to 1.5" to possibly 2" inches--some small cams work very well and the crack is solid.
content.location: Use the corner leading up to a large right facing dihedral for orientation--this is a crack system directly below a small pine tree and to the right of that corner.  All the moss is gone where it matters and the climb is safe.  As more climbers climb it the remaining moss in spots will disappear.

content.description: Between Mad Max and Crocodile Dundee.  5-6 bolts to chains.  Interesting face climbing to bulge.  Hidden jug makes bulge easy to navigate once you find it.
content.protection: Bolts.  5-6 quickdraws are all that is necessary
content.location: Between Mad Max and Crocodile Dundee on the Outback Wall

content.description: Just right of crack  Quite easy if you jam in the crack.  More challenging if you layback up the outside flakes.
content.location: Just  right of Arete (large crack in the middle of the wall)

content.description: Route goes up and left and then up again. 3rd route from the left of the Outback Wall.  Very well bolted easy lead.  Lots of rope drag.  It would be wise to extend the draws on the right side where it starts with full length slings to reduce drag.  Once you climb to what appears to be the top - you have about 20' more to go on dirty slab to reach the chains.
content.location: 3rd route from the left on Outback Wall

content.description: Far left of Outback wall. Shares the first few bolts with Walkabout.  When you reach the slab instead of turning to the right and going up the slab to the chains at Walkabout - continue directly up over a small roof to the chains.

Begin by going over a blocky low-angle section to a ledge (a block). Continue straight up the face through horizontal cracks (plenty of cam placements). At the top, the wall steepens, with the crux being the last move before the chains.
content.protection: Fully bolted (7 bolts). It can be led easily on trad gear (small cams to #0.75 Camalot, optional larger cams through the blocks at the start). Two bolts with chains at the top, or walk off.
content.location: Look for a large, obvious, and easy crack (fully bolted) at about 1/3 of the way along the cliff from right to left. This route is to the left of that crack.  The next route to the left is the slightly easier Wall O.B.

content.description: This is a fun but really easy route that climbs up through some unique rock.
The crux on this route is moving over the third bolt. It's a fun reachy route that has a little of everything.
content.location: Just left of White Whale. Make sure to NOT clip the glue in bolts or you are getting onto White Whale. Routes are practically on top of one another.

content.description: Middle of the wall.  Very large crack with lots of blocky holds.  Easy first lead very well protected.  Some of the bolts are deep in the crack.
content.location: Middle of the wall - large visible crack between Didgerdoo to the left and Max Max Crax to the right
